---

## Implementation Plan: Custom Theme System for T3 Code Editor

This plan addresses all four design questions and produces a fully self-contained theme system that works within the existing monorepo constraints (no new dependencies, no build config changes).

---

### Overview of Files

| Action | File |
|---|---|
| CREATE | `packages/contracts/src/theme.ts` |
| MODIFY | `packages/contracts/src/index.ts` (add one line) |
| CREATE | `apps/web/src/themes.ts` |
| MODIFY | `apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts` (replace) |
| MODIFY | `apps/web/src/index.css` (add CSS blocks) |
| CREATE | `apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx` |
| MODIFY | `apps/web/src/routes/_chat.settings.tsx` (replace Appearance section) |

---

### Step 1 — `packages/contracts/src/theme.ts` (CREATE)

This file uses the same `Schema` pattern every other contracts file uses.

```typescript
import { Schema } from "effect";

// The 12-field palette that each built-in theme must provide.
// All values are concrete color strings (oklch/hex) — NOT CSS var() references.
// This is intentional: palette fields are used directly in preview swatches.
export const ThemeColorPalette = Schema.Struct({
  background:       Schema.String, // main app background
  foreground:       Schema.String, // default text color
  accent:           Schema.String, // interactive highlight background
  accentForeground: Schema.String, // text on accent surfaces
  primary:          Schema.String, // brand / CTA color
  primaryForeground:Schema.String, // text on primary surfaces
  muted:            Schema.String, // subtle surface
  mutedForeground:  Schema.String, // de-emphasized text
  sidebar:          Schema.String, // sidebar panel background
  editor:           Schema.String, // code editor background
  terminal:         Schema.String, // terminal panel background
  statusBar:        Schema.String, // bottom status bar background
});
export type ThemeColorPalette = typeof ThemeColorPalette.Type;

// The union of all valid theme identifiers (including "system" as a meta-choice).
export const AppThemeId = Schema.Literals([
  "system",
  "t3-dark",
  "t3-light",
  "t3-midnight",
]);
export type AppThemeId = typeof AppThemeId.Type;

// A complete named theme entry — id + human label + palette.
export const AppTheme = Schema.Struct({
  id:      AppThemeId,
  label:   Schema.String,
  palette: ThemeColorPalette,
});
export type AppTheme = typeof AppTheme.Type;
```

**Design decision rationale for palette fields being concrete values:** The `preview swatches` question (design question 4) requires that the `ThemeSelector` component renders colored circles using actual color values. If the palette only stored `var()` references, the color would not render without first resolving CSS custom properties, which is impossible in a React style prop. Concrete oklch/hex values stored in the schema solve this natively.

---

### Step 2 — `packages/contracts/src/index.ts` (MODIFY)

Add exactly one line at the end of the file:

```typescript
export * from "./theme";
```

The full file will have 15 lines (the existing 14 plus this new one).

---

### Step 3 — `apps/web/src/themes.ts` (CREATE)

This file lives in `apps/web/src/` alongside `appSettings.ts`. It does three things:

1. Defines the concrete color values for all three built-in themes.
2. Provides a `buildThemeCssVars()` function that maps the 12 palette fields onto the full set of Tailwind CSS custom properties used in `index.css`.
3. Provides `BUILT_IN_THEMES` and `THEME_LOOKUP` convenience exports.

#### Color Values

**t3-dark** (the default dark mode — high contrast, blueish-neutral):
```
background:        oklch(0.118 0.008 264)   // ~#0f0f13 near-black with blue tint
foreground:        oklch(0.940 0.004 264)   // #efeff5 near-white
accent:            oklch(0.200 0.010 264)   // #1c1c28 slightly elevated surface
accentForeground:  oklch(0.940 0.004 264)
primary:           oklch(0.588 0.217 264)   // brand purple-blue (matches existing dark primary)
primaryForeground: oklch(1.000 0 0)        // white
muted:             oklch(0.190 0.008 264)   // #18182
mutedForeground:   oklch(0.560 0.012 264)   // gray
sidebar:           oklch(0.100 0.008 264)   // slightly darker than background
editor:            oklch(0.108 0.006 264)   // ~#0d0d11
terminal:          oklch(0.090 0.005 264)   // deepest black
statusBar:         oklch(0.488 0.217 264)   // brand color
```

**t3-light** (the default light mode — warm white, same brand):
```
background:        oklch(1.000 0 0)         // white
foreground:        oklch(0.200 0.005 264)   // near-black text
accent:            oklch(0.955 0.005 264)   // very light gray
accentForeground:  oklch(0.200 0.005 264)
primary:           oklch(0.488 0.217 264)   // brand (matches existing light primary)
primaryForeground: oklch(1.000 0 0)
muted:             oklch(0.960 0.004 264)   // #f5f5f8
mutedForeground:   oklch(0.500 0.010 264)   // medium gray
sidebar:           oklch(0.975 0.004 264)   // slightly off-white
editor:            oklch(0.990 0.002 264)   // near-white
terminal:          oklch(0.130 0.006 264)   // dark terminal in light mode
statusBar:         oklch(0.488 0.217 264)   // brand color
```

**t3-midnight** (a distinct dark variant — deep navy/indigo, higher saturation):
```
background:        oklch(0.110 0.028 274)   // deep navy
foreground:        oklch(0.920 0.012 264)   // slightly warm white
accent:            oklch(0.190 0.032 274)   // elevated navy surface
accentForeground:  oklch(0.920 0.012 264)
primary:           oklch(0.630 0.240 280)   // more vivid indigo/violet
primaryForeground: oklch(1.000 0 0)
muted:             oklch(0.175 0.025 274)   // deep muted navy
mutedForeground:   oklch(0.560 0.020 274)   // steel-blue gray
sidebar:           oklch(0.090 0.030 274)   // darkest navy
editor:            oklch(0.100 0.025 274)
terminal:          oklch(0.075 0.020 274)   // nearly-black navy
statusBar:         oklch(0.630 0.240 280)   // vivid indigo
```

#### `buildThemeCssVars()` function

This is the most important implementation detail. It translates the 12-field palette into the full set of CSS custom properties needed to match the Tailwind design token system in `index.css`.

The mapping logic (expressed as a lookup from palette to CSS var name):

| CSS custom property | Value source |
|---|---|
| `--background` | `palette.background` |
| `--foreground` | `palette.foreground` |
| `--card` | derived from `background` (e.g., `color-mix(in oklch, ${palette.background} 98%, white)`) — but since inline styles don't support `color-mix`, use direct oklch values slightly lighter than background |
| `--card-foreground` | `palette.foreground` |
| `--popover` | same as `--card` |
| `--popover-foreground` | `palette.foreground` |
| `--primary` | `palette.primary` |
| `--primary-foreground` | `palette.primaryForeground` |
| `--secondary` | `palette.muted` |
| `--secondary-foreground` | `palette.foreground` |
| `--muted` | `palette.muted` |
| `--muted-foreground` | `palette.mutedForeground` |
| `--accent` | `palette.accent` |
| `--accent-foreground` | `palette.accentForeground` |
| `--destructive` | `oklch(0.628 0.258 29.23)` (constant red — not theme-specific) |
| `--destructive-foreground` | light/dark variant of red (constant) |
| `--border` | derived: for dark themes `oklch(${l} ${c} ${h} / 12%)` alpha — for inline, use a concrete slightly-lighter-than-bg value |
| `--input` | similar to border but slightly more opaque |
| `--ring` | `palette.primary` |
| `--sidebar` | `palette.sidebar` (new var) |
| `--editor` | `palette.editor` (new var) |
| `--terminal` | `palette.terminal` (new var) |
| `--status-bar` | `palette.statusBar` (new var) |
| `color-scheme` | `"dark"` for t3-dark and t3-midnight; `"light"` for t3-light |

Since `document.documentElement.style.setProperty()` cannot use `color-mix()` or `--alpha()` syntax (those require CSS parser), `--border` and `--input` need to be expressed as concrete alpha-based values. The cleanest approach is to use `oklch(... / 0.12)` for border (which `style.setProperty()` handles fine) by computing that in the helper function.

For `--card`, use a slightly lighter/darker variant of background. A clean rule: for dark themes add ~3% lightness; for light themes subtract ~1% lightness. This can be computed directly in oklch by adjusting the L channel by ±0.015 in the helper.

#### Function signature:

```typescript
export function buildThemeCssVars(
  palette: ThemeColorPalette,
  isDark: boolean,
): Record<string, string>
```

Returns a flat `{ "--background": "...", "--foreground": "..." }` object ready to be applied via `setProperty`.

#### `BUILT_IN_THEMES` and `THEME_LOOKUP`:

```typescript
export const BUILT_IN_THEMES: readonly AppTheme[] = [
  { id: "t3-dark", label: "Dark", palette: T3_DARK_PALETTE },
  { id: "t3-light", label: "Light", palette: T3_LIGHT_PALETTE },
  { id: "t3-midnight", label: "Midnight", palette: T3_MIDNIGHT_PALETTE },
];

export const THEME_LOOKUP = new Map<string, AppTheme>(
  BUILT_IN_THEMES.map((t) => [t.id, t]),
);

// The "system" pseudo-theme just aliases dark/light based on OS preference
export const SYSTEM_DARK_THEME_ID: AppThemeId = "t3-dark";
export const SYSTEM_LIGHT_THEME_ID: AppThemeId = "t3-light";
```

---

### Step 4 — `apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts` (REPLACE)

This is a full replacement. It extends the existing `useSyncExternalStore` pattern while:
- Expanding `Theme` from `"light" | "dark" | "system"` to `AppThemeId` (which includes `"system" | "t3-dark" | "t3-light" | "t3-midnight"`).
- Migrating old stored values at read time.
- Applying themes by writing CSS custom properties via `setProperty()` rather than only toggling `.dark`.
- Still toggling `.dark` for Tailwind `dark:` utilities.

**Design decision — CSS application strategy (design question 1):**

Use `document.documentElement.style.setProperty()` to inject CSS vars dynamically. The reason: inline styles on `documentElement` have highest specificity, overriding the `@variant dark` block in `index.css`. This gives t3-midnight full control over all variables even when `.dark` is set. The alternative, `[data-theme="t3-midnight"] { ... }` selectors in CSS, would require all theme data to be hardcoded in the CSS file, making runtime extensibility harder and duplicating the color data.

The `.dark` class must still be set because Tailwind's `dark:` prefix classes (`dark:bg-input/32`, `dark:before:shadow-...` etc. visible throughout the component files) are conditioned on it. For t3-midnight (dark), `.dark` is set; for t3-light, it is cleared.

**Key exported types and functions:**

```typescript
// The new storage type is AppThemeId (the full set including "system")
type AppThemeId = "system" | "t3-dark" | "t3-light" | "t3-midnight";

// Migration: old "dark" → "t3-dark", "light" → "t3-light", "system" stays
function migrateStoredTheme(raw: string | null): AppThemeId

// Resolves "system" → "t3-dark" or "t3-light" based on OS preference
function resolveThemeId(themeId: AppThemeId): "t3-dark" | "t3-light" | "t3-midnight"

// Applies theme to DOM: sets CSS vars + toggles .dark + handles transitions
function applyTheme(themeId: AppThemeId, suppressTransitions?: boolean): void

export function useTheme(): {
  theme: AppThemeId;               // stored value (may be "system")
  resolvedTheme: AppThemeId;       // the actual resolved theme (never "system")
  resolvedPalette: ThemeColorPalette; // for swatch previews
  setTheme: (next: AppThemeId) => void;
}
```

**Migration logic in `getStored()`:**

```typescript
function migrateStoredTheme(raw: string | null): AppThemeId {
  if (raw === "dark") return "t3-dark";
  if (raw === "light") return "t3-light";
  if (raw === "system" || raw === "t3-dark" || raw === "t3-light" || raw === "t3-midnight") {
    return raw;
  }
  return "system"; // default fallback
}
```

**`applyTheme()` implementation:**

```typescript
function applyTheme(themeId: AppThemeId, suppressTransitions = false): void {
  if (suppressTransitions) {
    document.documentElement.classList.add("no-transitions");
  }

  const resolvedId = resolveThemeId(themeId); // "t3-dark" | "t3-light" | "t3-midnight"
  const theme = THEME_LOOKUP.get(resolvedId)!;
  const isDark = resolvedId !== "t3-light";

  // Toggle .dark for Tailwind dark: utilities
  document.documentElement.classList.toggle("dark", isDark);

  // Apply all CSS custom properties via inline styles (highest specificity,
  // overrides the @variant dark block in index.css for full theme control)
  const vars = buildThemeCssVars(theme.palette, isDark);
  for (const [prop, value] of Object.entries(vars)) {
    document.documentElement.style.setProperty(prop, value);
  }

  if (suppressTransitions) {
    document.documentElement.offsetHeight; // force reflow
    requestAnimationFrame(() => {
      document.documentElement.classList.remove("no-transitions");
    });
  }
}
```

**`ThemeSnapshot` shape:**

```typescript
type ThemeSnapshot = {
  theme: AppThemeId;
  systemDark: boolean;
};
```

**`resolvedTheme` logic in `useTheme()`:**

```typescript
const resolvedTheme: "t3-dark" | "t3-light" | "t3-midnight" =
  theme === "system"
    ? (snapshot.systemDark ? "t3-dark" : "t3-light")
    : theme as "t3-dark" | "t3-light" | "t3-midnight";
const resolvedPalette = THEME_LOOKUP.get(resolvedTheme)!.palette;
```

**Backward compatibility (design question 2):** The `migrateStoredTheme()` function handles old `"dark"` / `"light"` values transparently. The write path (in `setTheme`) always writes the new `AppThemeId` values, so after the first user interaction the migration is permanent. The module-load call `applyTheme(getStored())` will correctly read old values via migration.

---

### Step 5 — `apps/web/src/index.css` (MODIFY)

Add new CSS custom property declarations for the new zone-specific variables. These go in the `:root` block to define defaults (the inline style injection from `useTheme` will override them at runtime).

**In the `:root` block, after the existing vars, add:**

```css
/* Zone-specific theme vars (set by useTheme via inline style) */
--sidebar: oklch(0.975 0.004 264);
--editor: oklch(0.990 0.002 264);
--terminal: oklch(0.090 0.005 264);
--status-bar: oklch(0.488 0.217 264);
```

**In the `@variant dark { }` block, after the existing vars, add:**

```css
--sidebar: oklch(0.100 0.008 264);
--editor: oklch(0.108 0.006 264);
--terminal: oklch(0.090 0.005 264);
--status-bar: oklch(0.488 0.217 264);
```

**In the `@theme inline { }` block, add four mappings:**

```css
--color-sidebar: var(--sidebar);
--color-editor: var(--editor);
--color-terminal: var(--terminal);
--color-status-bar: var(--status-bar);
```

These additions allow Tailwind classes like `bg-sidebar`, `bg-editor`, `bg-terminal`, `bg-status-bar` to work in components that need them. They also establish correct fallback values before the JS executes.

**No changes to `@custom-variant dark` declaration** — that stays as is and remains needed for `dark:` utility support throughout the component library.

---

### Step 6 — `apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx` (CREATE)

This new component replaces the current radio button list in the Appearance section. It renders three visual swatch cards plus a "System" option.

**Structure:**

```tsx
import type { AppThemeId } from "@t3tools/contracts";
import { BUILT_IN_THEMES, SYSTEM_DARK_THEME_ID, SYSTEM_LIGHT_THEME_ID } from "../themes";
import { useTheme } from "../hooks/useTheme";
import { cn } from "~/lib/utils";

interface ThemeSelectorProps {
  value: AppThemeId;
  onChange: (next: AppThemeId) => void;
}

export function ThemeSelector({ value, onChange }: ThemeSelectorProps)
```

**Layout:** A 2-column grid on small screens, 4-column on wider. Each cell is a button with:
- A swatch preview block (miniature UI mockup showing sidebar + editor + accent colors)
- Theme label below
- A selected indicator (ring or checkmark)

**Swatch preview structure (per theme card):**

```tsx
// The swatch shows a tiny side-by-side layout:
// [sidebar strip | editor area with a colored status dot]
<div
  className="w-full rounded-md overflow-hidden border"
  style={{ aspectRatio: "16/10" }}
>
  {/* Sidebar strip */}
  <div
    className="h-full"
    style={{ width: "28%", float: "left", background: theme.palette.sidebar }}
  />
  {/* Editor area */}
  <div
    className="h-full relative"
    style={{
      marginLeft: "28%",
      background: theme.palette.editor,
    }}
  >
    {/* Status bar at bottom */}
    <div
      className="absolute bottom-0 inset-x-0 h-[12%]"
      style={{ background: theme.palette.statusBar }}
    />
    {/* Fake code lines */}
    <div className="absolute top-[15%] left-[8%] right-[8%] flex flex-col gap-[6%]">
      <div
        className="h-[8%] rounded-full opacity-60"
        style={{ width: "65%", background: theme.palette.primary }}
